            <lb/>
The Science of Nature depends in a<lb/>
great measure upon artificial inventions for<lb/>
assisting the faculties of the mind and for<lb/>
increasing the activity of genius.<lb/>
And it requires for its advancement a State<lb/>
of society in which active patronage is<lb/>
offered; and in which it is assisted no less<lb/>
by the diffusion of letters than by the<lb/>
application of industry, riches and power<lb/>
to its numerous and <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">diversified</del>
            <lb/>
diversified objects.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
It is not therefore <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">necessary</del> extraordinary<lb/>
that the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">spirit</hi> of observation and of<lb/>
experiment, which maintained with difficulty<lb/>
a sickly existance even in the most <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">splendid</hi>
            <lb/>
and happy eras of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag2"
                ref="#place_155"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag2" type="place">
          Rome
        </name>
            </rs>, should have<lb/>
disappeared altogether at the <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">time</unclear> of Her<lb/>
decline and degradation when turbulence<lb/>
at Home, feebleness abroad and indulgence<lb/>
in the grossest luxury had prepared the<lb/>
way for the total downfall of the state<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#place_475"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag3" type="place">
          Egypt
        </name>
            </rs> recorded as the parent of Science<lb/>
in the most remote antiquity was destined<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
by a singular occurrence of circumstances<lb/>
to become her <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">nurse</hi> in a later period<lb/>
And philosophy driven from the West by<lb/>
persecution by the ravages of Barbarians<lb/>
and the tumult of savage warfare found<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">a transient refuge</hi> within the walls <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag4" ref="#place_1135" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag4" type="place">
          Alexandria
        </name>
               </rs>.</hi>
            <lb/>
Towards the close of the fourth century<lb/>
at the time when the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#misc_538"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag5">
          Goths
        </term>
            </rs> were conquering<lb/>
the finest provinces of Europe and keeping<lb/>
the Romans in continual alarm this city<lb/>
enjoyed a profound peace and afforded<lb/>
an asylum to Students from all parts<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Empire</hi> -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
The School of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#place_1135"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="place">
          Alexandria
        </name>
            </rs> produced several<lb/>
laborious Geometricians; but the greatest<lb/>
ornament belonging to it and the most<lb/>
Illustrious Philosopher was <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#person_1049"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag7" type="person">
          Hypatia
        </name>
            </rs> daughter<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag8"
                ref="#person_1050"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag8" type="person">
          Theon
        </name>
            </rs> -<lb/>
This celebrated lady is said to have<lb/>
been equally distinguished for Her skill<lb/>
in Mathematical in general science<lb/>
and in the knowledge of Nature and<lb/>
of the Earth.<lb/>
And that She applied herself to<lb/>
experiment is evident from one of her<lb/>
invention the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag9"
                ref="#misc_850"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag9">
          Hydrometer
        </term>
            </rs> the instrument<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
now in common use for ascertaining<lb/>
the relative weights of fluids -<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag10"
                ref="#person_1049"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag10" type="person">
          Hypatia
        </name>
            </rs> taught after her fathers death<lb/>
in her native city.- By the eloquence<lb/>
and soundness of her doctrines she excited<lb/>
the highest zeal for moral and intellectual<lb/>
improvement amongst her disciples.<lb/>
She was no less admirable for the grace<lb/>
and loviliness of her person than for<lb/>
talents and virtue and she shone with<lb/>
greater lustre being as it were a<lb/>
single brilliant Star in a night<lb/>
of clouds and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">obscurity</hi> -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
Learning flourished at <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag11"
                ref="#place_1135"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag11" type="place">
          Alexandria
        </name>
            </rs> for nearly<lb/>
two hundred years; but literature and metaphysics<lb/>
seem to have been more attended to than<lb/>
experimental knowledge -<lb/>
of the improvement made however we are<lb/>
almost wholly ignorant.<lb/>
For the <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">same</add> causes which put a stop to<lb/>
the future progress of science destroyed all<lb/>
the records of the advancement that had<lb/>
been made.<lb/>
The city was conquered by the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag12"
                ref="#misc_273"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag12">
          Saracens
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
and the most magnificent and perfect<lb/>
library in the world burnt by the<lb/>
command of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag13"
                ref="#person_1051"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag13" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">omar</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
Philosophy and letters were taken away<lb/>
from the people and they were obliged<lb/>
by the force of sword and of fire to<lb/>
substitute for them the absurdities and<lb/>
impostures of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag14"
                ref="#otherwork_316"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag14">
            Koran.-
        </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
All was again ignorance and darkness till<lb/>
the eighth century when a feeble gleam<lb/>
of light burst forth in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag15"
                ref="#place_1212"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag15" type="place">
          Arabia
        </name>
            </rs>.<lb/>
And the patronage of two celebrated Caliphs<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag16"
                ref="#person_136"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag16" type="person">
          Al and
        </name>
            </rs>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#person_1052"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag17" type="person">
          Al kept alive
        </name>
            </rs> for a<lb/>
short time the spark of inquiry but at<lb/>
this period there were no permanent materials<lb/>
for it to act upon.<lb/>
The spirit of Science and that of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
                ref="#misc_678"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag18">
          Mahometism
        </term>
            </rs> like the good and evil<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
principles of Zoraster were incapable of<lb/>
being reconciled.<lb/>
Improvement languished in the reign of<lb/>
the later Sovereigns of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag19"
                ref="#place_1311"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag19" type="place">
          Baghdad
        </name>
            </rs> and it<lb/>
perished altogether with the Empire<lb/>
which was one of the first that fell<lb/>
beneath the rising power of the Turks.<lb/>
Very few words of importance have been<lb/>
transmitted to us from the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag20"
                ref="#misc_273"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag20">
          Saracens
        </term>
            </rs>, and<lb/>
the details that we are in possession of<lb/>
with regard to the short literary history<lb/>
of this people are principally valuable<lb/>
on account of their connection about<lb/>
the time of the crusades with the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
establishment of a particular <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">philosophical</hi>
            <lb/>
sect in Europe which had the greatest<lb/>
influence upon the progress of Natural<lb/>
Science of chemistry and of Geology.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag21"
                ref="#person_1054"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag21" type="person">
          Gebir
        </name>
            </rs> and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag22"
                ref="#person_1053"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag22" type="person">
          Rhases
        </name>
            </rs> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag23"
                ref="#place_1311"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag23" type="place">
          Bagdat
        </name>
            </rs> are said<lb/>
to have been the first men who<lb/>
pursued the applications of Chemistry with the<lb/>
view of ascertaining the nature of the<lb/>
bodies belonging to the Earth and for<lb/>
effecting changes in them -<lb/>
And they are the philosophers to whom<lb/>
the earliest Alchemists of the West<lb/>
ascribe the origin of their Art.<lb/>
Alchemy as at first professed was considered<lb/>
as an universal <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Science</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
It was regarded not merely as affording<lb/>
the means of converting other metals into<lb/>
Gold and as providing remedies for all<lb/>
Maladies; but as laying open the<lb/>
great secret of Nature and as explaining<lb/>
the phenomena of the Earth of the<lb/>
sea of the Air and of the subterranean<lb/>
mineral <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">kindom</del> kingdom.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag24"
                ref="#person_061"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag24" type="person">
          Albertus Magnus
        </name>
            </rs> and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag25"
                ref="#person_324"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag25" type="person">
          Roger Bacon
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
who are the first persons recorded as<lb/>
applying themselves to experiment in<lb/>
the dark ages seem both to have been<lb/>
guided by very philosophical views<lb/>
and to have had as their principle<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="13"
                xml:id="pb-13"
                facs="#i13"/>
            <lb/>
objects the advancement of Science.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag26"
                ref="#person_324"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag26" type="person">
          the elder Bacon
        </name>
            </rs> confesses in his great<lb/>
work that He gained the foundation of<lb/>
his knowledge from the Arabian writers<lb/>
upon whom he bestows high and<lb/>
unqualified praise.<lb/>
This great man evidently studied<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Nature</hi> and the production of the Earth<lb/>
with the views of a philosopher but<lb/>
his knowledge was so superior as to be<lb/>
unintelligible in the age in which he<lb/>
lived. The wonders produced by chemistry<lb/>
were referred by the people to <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">evil</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">spirits</del> the agency of evil spirits<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="14"
                xml:id="pb-14"
                facs="#i14"/>
            <lb/>
and a very short time after He had<lb/>
written a book to prove the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">nonexistence</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of Magic</hi> He was himself persecuted<lb/>
as an <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">enchanter</hi>, and He was imprisoned<lb/>
in 1278 by the Franciscans for having brought<lb/>
the order into disrepute by pretending<lb/>
to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">natural wisdom</hi> and by exercising<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">unholy</hi> and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">supernatural powers</hi>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag27"
                ref="#person_324"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag27" type="person">
          Roger Bacon
        </name>
            </rs> appears to have<lb/>
made use of the philosophical and<lb/>
experimental method of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag28"
                ref="#misc_273"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag28">
          Saracens
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
without following any of the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
absurdities of their doctrines, He had seen<lb/>
admirable changes produced in bodies and<lb/>
He knew not the limits of the operation of Nature<lb/>
By Him the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">production</hi> of Gold and the<lb/>
transmutation of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Metals</hi> were considered only<lb/>
as <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">objects</hi> worthy of investigation; but<lb/>
He never affirmed confidently concerning them.<lb/>
He had made many important discoveries<lb/>
and particularly that of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag29"
                ref="#misc_680"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag29">
          one expensive compound
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
similar to Gunpowder -<lb/>
And yet he seldom suffered his imagination<lb/>
to cloud his reason and He was no<lb/>
enthusiast with regard to the merit of<lb/>
his inventions.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
He possessed the modest and dignified feeling<lb/>
of Science; but most of the Alchemists who<lb/>
flourished in the next century were of a very<lb/>
different complexion. They formed themselves<lb/>
into a fraternity They professed to be<lb/>
in possession of great and important <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">secrets</unclear>
            <lb/>
They connected a peculiar mysticism<lb/>
with their philosophical doctrines.<lb/>
They attached to Alchemy a language<lb/>
similar to that which had been employed<lb/>
in the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag30"
                ref="#person_085"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag30" type="person">
          Platonic
        </name>
            </rs> philosophy and they<lb/>
pretended <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to</del> not only <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to</del> a knowledge<lb/>
of the materials of the Globe and the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
changes of things but likewise to an<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">organization</del> acquaintance with the elemen<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ts</add>
            <lb/>
and the spiritual powers by which they<lb/>
supposed these were governed.-<lb/>
The Arabians had blended in their<lb/>
philosophy many brilliant superstitions<lb/>
concerning the agency of a class of beings<lb/>
supposed to be superior to Man and<lb/>
possessed of great knowledge and of<lb/>
high power.-<lb/>
And the notion of fa<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">i</add>ries and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag31"
                ref="#misc_211"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag31">
          Genii
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
which have been depicted with so much<lb/>
vividness of fancy and loveliness of<lb/>
description in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag32"
                ref="#otherwork_123"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag32">
            the thousand and one<lb/>nights
        </bibl>
            </rs> seems to have been adopted under a<lb/>
new form.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
By the adepts of this period <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in Europe</hi>
            <lb/>
who though they altered the denominations<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the <del rend="strikethrough">
                  <unclear>serif</unclear>
               </del> spiritual</hi>
