                rend="underline">Agents created</hi>
            <lb/>
by the fancy of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the orientalists.</hi> still<lb/>
attribute to them similar attributes and<lb/>
similar relations to Man.-<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag33"
                ref="#person_069"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag33" type="person">
          Agrippa
        </name>
            </rs> in his work on the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">occult</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Sciences</hi> endeavours to devellope a general<lb/>
system of the philosophy of the Earth<lb/>
and He begins by supposing that all<lb/>
things on the terrestrial Globe are<lb/>
under the protection of influences residing<lb/>
in the stars and of Good and evil <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag34"
                ref="#misc_211"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag34">
          Genii
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
and that true knowledge can be derived<lb/>
only from a communication with those<lb/>
