            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
spiritual beings.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag35"
                ref="#person_069"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag35" type="person">
          Agrippa
        </name>
            </rs> considered <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">fire</hi> as the great<lb/>
active principle in Nature and from<lb/>
its operation upon earth which He regards<lb/>
as a passive element He conceived the<lb/>
great appearances of the external world<lb/>
produced.-<lb/>
Water and Air He thought were more<lb/>
capable of being converted into each other<lb/>
and yet He considered this as a vital<lb/>
principle which existed in almost all<lb/>
substances and as essential to their<lb/>
composition and their nature.-<lb/>
