Both <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag64"
                ref="#person_062"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag64" type="person">
          Agricola
        </name>
            </rs> and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag65"
                ref="#person_1059"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag65" type="person">
          Erckern
        </name>
            </rs> considered<lb/>
the metals as incapable of being transmuted<lb/>
into each other and they regarded<lb/>
them as produced by certain operations of<lb/>
Nature which cannot be imitated by<lb/>
artificial means.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="32"
                xml:id="pb-32"
                facs="#i32"/>
            <lb/>
The period in which these two<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mineralogists</hi>wrote was the great era<lb/>
of improvement in the general methods<lb/>
of the natural sciences.-<lb/>
It was the period in which the<lb/>
death blow was given to Alchemy by<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag66"
                ref="#person_757"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag66" type="person">
          Gassendi
        </name>
            </rs> and <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Kelp</del>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag67"
                ref="#person_363"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag67" type="person">
          Kepler
        </name>
            </rs> who both<lb/>
answered for Fludd the last public<lb/>
defender of the Rosicrusians -<lb/>
It was the period in which <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag68" ref="#person_283" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag68" type="person">
          Gallileo
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <lb/>
pursued the paths of experimental<lb/>
enquiry; And in which <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag69"
                ref="#person_124"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag69" type="person">
          the second<lb/>illustrous Bacon
        </name>
            </rs> had the honour of<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="33"
                xml:id="pb-33"
                facs="#i33"/>
            <lb/>
establishing <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Sciences</hi> upon their<lb/>
true and immutable foundations.-<lb/>
Many scientific persons <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag70"
                ref="#person_124"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag70" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">before Bacon</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
had pursued the method of Experiment<lb/>
in all its precision, many had dared<lb/>
to despise the logic and forms of the<lb/>
ancients, but He was the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">first</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">philosopher</hi> who laid down plans for<lb/>
extending knowledge of universal application<lb/>
who ventured to assert that all the sciences<lb/>
could be nothing more than expressions<lb/>
of facts and that the first step towards<lb/>
the attainment of real discovery was<lb/>
the humiliating confession of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">ignorance</hi>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="34"
                xml:id="pb-34"
                facs="#i34"/>
            <lb/>
Bacon was prepared by Nature by<lb/>
education and by his habit of study for<lb/>
effecting the great revolution in philosophy<lb/>
His knowledge was extensive his instances<lb/>
were copious. His Genius was equally<lb/>
capable of develloping the lighter and<lb/>
the more profound relations of things.<lb/>
He professed a strong feeling but it<lb/>
was uniformly directed by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">reason</hi> -<lb/>
He was gifted with a vivid imagination<lb/>
but it was modified by a most correct<lb/>
taste - <lb/>
The influence of rank and of situation<lb/>
assisted his views - The public was prepared<lb/>
to receive them, and he was enabled<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="35"
                xml:id="pb-35"
                facs="#i35"/>
            <lb/>
to devellope his opinions with full<lb/>
confidence that they would be adopted<lb/>
with reverence even in his own time and<lb/>
that they would carry his memory into<lb/>
future ages with <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great</hi> and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">with</hi>
            <lb/>
unchanging Glory.-<lb/>
+ The pursuit of the new method of investigat<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ion</add>
            <lb/>
in a very short time wholly altered the<lb/>
face of every department of Natural<lb/>
Knowledge but their influence was in<lb/>
no case more distinct that in the advance<add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">ment</add>
            <lb/>
of Geology and chemistry; though much<lb/>
labour had been bestowed upon these<lb/>
extensive fields of investigation they<lb/>
had hitherto as we have seen been little<lb/>
productive.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="36"
                xml:id="pb-36"
                facs="#i36"/>
            <lb/>
Speculation had been misplaced observation<lb/>
confined and experiment principally<lb/>
directed rather towards impossible than<lb/>
to practicable things.<lb/>
in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">novel system</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">hypotheses</hi> was<lb/>
exploded except as a guide to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">actual</hi>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">truths</del>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">trials</hi> - Combinations of thoughts<lb/>
were considered as truths only when<lb/>
conformable <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to Nature</hi> and not <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">merely</del>
            <lb/>
when they merely expressed the caprices<lb/>
of the imagination and those enquiries<lb/>
only were regarded as valuable which<lb/>
were made upon the hidden sensible<lb/>
properties of things and upon the<lb/>
existing relations of facts.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="37"
                xml:id="pb-37"
                facs="#i37"/>
            <lb/>
(One of the first persons who applied <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">with</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">zeal</hi> to the investigation of the Theory of<lb/>
the Earth after enlightened views and<lb/>
distinct plans was <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag71" ref="#person_246" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag71" type="person">
          Robert Hooke
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <lb/>
I <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">have</del> mentioned in a former lecture that the<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">he distinguished himself at a very early</del>
            <lb/>
illustrious Man distinguished himself at a very early<lb/>
age by his mechanical knowledge"<lb/>
And <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">that in his chemical Speculations " He</add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">his first efforts towards invention</del>
            <lb/>
developed in a most consistent <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">view</del> &amp; penetrati ng<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">marked a high degree of talent.-</del>
            <lb/>
view the general theory of combustion<lb/>
But I can with pleasure mention him again<lb/>
His genius was <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">however</del> too powerful<lb/>
and too active to be limited to <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">any</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the pursuit</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">these<del rend="strikethrough">greater objects</del> considerable objects</add> and in the course of his<lb/>
scientific career he applied his <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">abilities</hi> to almost all the principal<lb/>
objects of investigation in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Natural</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Science</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="38"
                xml:id="pb-38"
                facs="#i38"/>
            <lb/>
He <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">applied</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">devoted</add> his attention equally to the great<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">In chemistry he develloped with a</del>
            <lb/>
laws of the globe considered as a part of the<lb/>
planetary system; &amp; to the minute changes<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">rapid yet penetrating view the general</del>
            <lb/>
&amp; imperceptitible alterations of the surface -<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">History of <hi rend="underline">combustion</hi>
            </del> - His opinions<lb/>
upon terrestrial motions are marked by a singular<lb/>
And his hypotheses of Earthquakes and<lb/>
volcanoes is scarcely exceeded by any of<lb/>
the refinements of Theory in modern times.<lb/>
Few men have done more than <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag72"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag72" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
and few have been more neglected and<lb/>
one of the principal reasons is that<lb/>
He was the contemporary of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag73"
                ref="#person_036"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag73" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Newton</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
whose just Glory and whose splendid<lb/>
discoveries concerning the great laws<lb/>
of the universe absorbed the attention<lb/>
of the philosophers of the age and<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="39"
                xml:id="pb-39"
                facs="#i39"/>
            <lb/>
and made them almost regardless<lb/>
of inferior inventions.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag74"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag74" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">geological speculations</hi>
            <lb/>
which were published after his death<lb/>
assuming as a fact the existence of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">shells and the</hi>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">and the</del> remains of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">marine</hi> animals in rocks and in hills<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">considerable elevation</hi> draws the<lb/>
conclusions, that these strata must have<lb/>
been at some period covered by the sea<lb/>
And after reasoning upon the general<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effects of Earthquakes</hi> and of Volcanic<lb/>
explosions He infers that there are<lb/>
no causes in nature more probable than<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="40"
                xml:id="pb-40"
                facs="#i40"/>
            <lb/>
these for the elevation of land of rock<lb/>
and of mountains from the bosom<lb/>
of the waters.<lb/>
He brings forward many chemical<lb/>
instances "to shew" that water is capable<lb/>
of dissolving and of depositing stoney<lb/>
matter and that its agency is fully<lb/>
adequate to the formation of strata.<lb/>
And He shews that both in modern and<lb/>
in ancient times several cases have<lb/>
occurred of Islands and of tracts of Land<lb/>
rising out of the sea in consequence<lb/>
of submarine Volcanoes -<lb/>
The ideas of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag75"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag75" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> are conceived with<lb/>
boldness and develloped with precision,<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="41"
                xml:id="pb-41"
                facs="#i41"/>
            <lb/>
In many principal parts of Theory He<lb/>
had anticipated the modern <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag76"
                ref="#person_085"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag76" type="person">
          Platonic
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
Philosophers: He seems however to have<lb/>
restrained his imagination. He has<lb/>
contented himself with demonstrating a<lb/>
certain part of the existing order of<lb/>
Nature without attempting a general<lb/>
system of the past change of the Globe<lb/>
and of its future destiny -<lb/>
Beccher lived at the same period<lb/>
as <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag77"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag77" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> like <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag78"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag78" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> He devoted his life<lb/>
to Science; but He selected one<lb/>
department and directed to Geological<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Gelogi</del> chemistry the whole of the<lb/>
power of his <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">genius</del>mind -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="42"
                xml:id="pb-42"
                facs="#i42"/>
            <lb/>
In his book called <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag79"
                ref="#otherwork_317"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag79">
            subterranean philosophy
        </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
published in latin in 1669<lb/>
He has given some very beautiful<lb/>
details with regard to the Mineral<lb/>
Kingdom and has offered views of<lb/>
Theory perfectly new - his ideas<lb/>
concerning combination and decomposit<lb/>
are of the most accurate nature<lb/>
his notion of an inflamable principle<lb/>
formed the foundation of the hypothesis<lb/>
of Hall - He gave to chemical philosophy<lb/>
new dominions and new instruments of<lb/>
investigation and He attempted to form<lb/>
a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">general</del> Theory in which all the<lb/>
operations of Nature should be explained<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="43"
                xml:id="pb-43"
                facs="#i43"/>
            <lb/>
illustrated by experiments of human invention<lb/>
Beccher with the sound judgment of<lb/>
a true philosopher assumes a certain<lb/>
primary order of things resulting from<lb/>
the creation of the Globe and He applies<lb/>
only to the solution of the phaenomena<lb/>
of the change, which have since taken<lb/>
place<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Water in the mineral kingdom</hi> and<lb/>
elastic vapours He considers as the great<lb/>
agents which have altered the position<lb/>
of strata and the direction of metalic<lb/>
veins and from the decomposition of<lb/>
certain rocks by these natural agents<lb/>
he supposes that new ones have been<lb/>
formed of a much <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">softer nature</hi> and<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="44"
                xml:id="pb-44"
                facs="#i44"/>
            <lb/>
fitted to become soils and to support<lb/>
vegetable Life -<lb/>
Beccher was born at spire in 1645<lb/>
He was for some time professor of medicine<lb/>
at <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
