            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag84"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag84" type="place">
          Cornwall
        </name>
            </rs> to further his experimental<lb/>
researches and to produce some of those<lb/>
works on Natural Science which<lb/>
will always confer honour on<lb/>
his name -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="45"
                xml:id="pb-45"
                facs="#i45"/>
            <lb/>
Hook and Beccher had contented themselves<lb/>
with <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">partial views</hi>;<lb/>
And the celebrated <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag85"
                ref="#person_1005"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag85" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Leibnitz</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> is the first<lb/>
philosopher who attempted a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">general</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">system</hi> of Geology -<lb/>
In his - <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag86"
                ref="#otherwork_318"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag86">
                  <add>Protogaea</add>
               </bibl>
            </rs> published in 1693 He enters<lb/>
upon the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great doctrines</hi> relating to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Globe</hi>
            <lb/>
the primary creation, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the deluge</hi> the changes<lb/>
that have been since produced and that<lb/>
will be produced in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">future ages</hi> -<lb/>
He assumes as the foundation of his reasoning<lb/>
the account of the creation given in the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sacred writings</hi>;-<lb/>
And He attempts to shew that the<lb/>
Globe at its origin must have existed in<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="46"
                xml:id="pb-46"
                facs="#i46"/>
            <lb/>
a state of igneous fusion in consequence of<lb/>
which it assumed its <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">spherical form</hi>;<lb/>
The heavier substances such as the metals<lb/>
He supposes to have occupied the centre<lb/>
and He conceives that the Rocks; which<lb/>
crystalized at first in regular strata were<lb/>
afterwards broken and raised into mountains<lb/>
by explosions taking place from beneath<lb/>
and the Chasms produced and filled with<lb/>
metalic veins.-<lb/>
The water which at first existed as<lb/>
highly rarified vapour He supposed to have<lb/>
been by degrees condensed and from its<lb/>
action in its heated state upon the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="47"
                xml:id="pb-47"
                facs="#i47"/>
            <lb/>
Land He conceives that a part of the<lb/>
surface was decomposed broken down and<lb/>
converted into a soil on which by the<lb/>
Almighty <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">fiat</unclear> vegetables and Animals<lb/>
were made to exist and the whole cloathed<lb/>
