                  <name xml:id="tag96" type="person">
          Leibnitz
        </name>
               </rs>
            </del>
            <lb/>
Another system which appeared about the<lb/>
same time as that of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag97"
                ref="#person_1005"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag97" type="person">
          Leibnitz
        </name>
            </rs> has excited<lb/>
infinitely more attention in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag98"
                ref="#place_159"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag98" type="place">
          Britain
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
I mean the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag99"
                ref="#otherwork_319"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag99">
            sacred Theory of the <del rend="strikethrough">New</del>
               </bibl>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
Earth by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag100"
                ref="#person_1001"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag100" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Burnet</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
In this work the Globe is supposed<lb/>
to have been created without irregularities<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">perfectly spherical</hi> and smooth having<lb/>
neither Hills Mountains nor Vallies -<lb/>
The land is supposed to Have been<lb/>
equally diffused above the Ocean<lb/>
and to have covered it as a thin<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="53"
                xml:id="pb-53"
                facs="#i53"/>
            <lb/>
Crust and the deluge is considered as<lb/>
having been occasioned by the breaking<lb/>
down of the land into the great abyss<lb/>
beneath an event which He supposes to<lb/>
have produced all the varieties of Sea<lb/>
and Earth that present exist the<lb/>
formation of Islands and the great<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">elevation of Continents</hi> -<lb/>
Burnet paints with all the feeling<lb/>
of an enthusiast the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">delightful state</hi>
            <lb/>
of the inhabitants of the Globe before<lb/>
the deluge in his hypotheses as there<lb/>
could have been no variety of Seasons<lb/>
He conceives that they must have<lb/>
enjoyed a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">perpetual Spring</hi>;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="54"
                xml:id="pb-54"
                facs="#i54"/>
            <lb/>
that the face of Heaven and the Sun<lb/>
and the Stars must have been exhibited<lb/>
to them in unclouded beauty.<lb/>
And that the whole of the Earth<lb/>
must have been green with perpetual<lb/>
vegetation.<lb/>
Burnet saw none of the errors of his<lb/>
system - He did not perceive that<lb/>
without the action of the waters of the<lb/>
sea upon the atmosphere there could<lb/>
be no rain no dews no rivers and<lb/>
consequently no plants and no animal life<lb/>
His mode of accounting for the moistening<lb/>
of the Earth by the filtration of water<lb/>
through the solid matter and its<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="55"
                xml:id="pb-55"
                facs="#i55"/>
            <lb/>
elevation into the air is <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">perfectly inadmiss</hi>-<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">ible</hi> and every one must allow that the<lb/>
feeling and taste of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag101"
                ref="#misc_853"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag101">
          Antediluvians
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
must have been very different from ours<lb/>
If they could derive more pleasure from<lb/>
the contemplation of a flat surface and<lb/>
an uniform sky than from the view<lb/>
of the variety of hill and dale of<lb/>
mountain and river scenery and<lb/>
the ever varying appearances of clouds<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag102"
                ref="#person_1062"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag102" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Keil</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> in his <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag103"
                ref="#otherwork_320"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag103">
            examination of the<lb/>
                  <hi rend="underline">sacred Theory</hi>
               </bibl>
            </rs> has distinctly proved<lb/>
that it is wholly incompatable with the<lb/>
general laws of the Globe and not<lb/>
conformable in the slightest degree to facts -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="56"
                xml:id="pb-56"
                facs="#i56"/>
            <lb/>
As a poetical Romance it is highly<lb/>
interesting and entertaining but as<lb/>
a philosophical opinion it is wholly<lb/>
unworthy of <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">opinion</del> attention and it<lb/>
affords one proof amongst many others<lb/>
of the folly of attempts to wrest the<lb/>
meaning of the sacred writings<lb/>
which express general truths so as<lb/>
to make them serve as supports for<lb/>
hypotheses of human invention so as<lb/>
to blend them with the visions<lb/>
and fancies of men - _|<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="57"
                xml:id="pb-57"
                facs="#i57"/>
            <lb/>
The last system which I shall mention in<lb/>
this Lecture is that of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag104"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag104" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Buffon</hi>
               </name>
            </rs>.-<lb/>
|_One of the most singular and extraordinary<lb/>
productions of the human mind, beauties and<lb/>
defects are blended in it and it is complete<lb/>
with ingenuity and with errors.<lb/>
|_<rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag105"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag105" type="person">
          Buffons
        </name>
            </rs> idea of the primary state of the Globe<lb/>
is wholly borrowed <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag106"
                ref="#person_1005"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag106" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">from Leibnitz</hi>.
        </name>
            </rs> He conceives<lb/>
it to have existed in igneous fusion; but despising<lb/>
the modern opinion of the Author of the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag107"
                ref="#otherwork_318"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag107">
            Protogaea
        </bibl>
            </rs> that such was its <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primary creation</hi> -<lb/>
He supposes it to have been produced from<lb/>
the ruins of another system to have been<lb/>
carried off from the Sun by the powerful<lb/>
impulse of a Comet and to have been moved -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="58"
                xml:id="pb-58"
                facs="#i58"/>
            <lb/>
into its present orbit by and the<lb/>
force of gravity -<lb/>
He fixes the era at which this great event<lb/>
is supposed to have taken place at a<lb/>
distance of time quite inconceivable -<lb/>
And He imagines three <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">different epochs</hi>
            <lb/>
in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the history</hi> of the cooling of the<lb/>
surface <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">before</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Marine Animals</hi> existed<lb/>
and five epochs before it was fitted for<lb/>
the residence of Land Animals &amp; of Man -<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag108"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag108" type="person">
          Buffon
        </name>
            </rs> brings forward two principal<lb/>
arguments in the support of his htypothesis<lb/>
and they are now both known to be<lb/>
founded upon false principles -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="59"
                xml:id="pb-59"
                facs="#i59"/>
            <lb/>
His first is that the temperature of the<lb/>
Earth is found higher the farther we<lb/>
penetrate beneath the surface<lb/>
The second is that the surface of the<lb/>
Earth is composed of matters which are<lb/>
almost all capable of being <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag109"
                ref="#chemical_509"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag109">
          vitrified
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
by Heat -<lb/>
Now it is well ascertained that except<lb/>
in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">volcanic countries</hi> at a considerable<lb/>
depth is the mean temperature of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Atmosphere</hi> and that it varies according<lb/>
to that mean in all the different<lb/>
climates so that it is evidently produced<lb/>
not by internal but by external causes<lb/>
not, by a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">cont</del> central fire but by the solar<lb/>
rays and the heat of the Air -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="60"
                xml:id="pb-60"
                facs="#i60"/>
            <lb/>
With regard to the other propositions<lb/>
it is certain that the greater number<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">our Rocks</hi> are wholly incapable of<lb/>
being fused by any Heat that we<lb/>
are able to apply to them;<lb/>
And though it is not improbable in<lb/>
a temperature such as that of the Sun<lb/>
they would become liquid; yet we<lb/>
have no right to make inference merely<lb/>
for the sake of forming <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">a Theory</hi>
            <lb/>
For a theory ought in all cases to be<lb/>
+ not an expression of conjecture but<lb/>
an arrangement of facts.<lb/>
The ideas of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag110"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag110" type="person">
          Buffon
        </name>
            </rs> concerning the<lb/>
changes of the Globe that are now<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="61"
                xml:id="pb-61"
                facs="#i61"/>
            <lb/>
taking place and the general order<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of Nature</hi> are scarcely less bold or less<lb/>
visionary than his notions concerning<lb/>
the origin of things -<lb/>
He conceives that the land and the sea<lb/>
are continually changing places. that<lb/>
from the action of rains of Rivers and of<lb/>
torrents the solid matter of the land is<lb/>
constantly divided decomposed and deposited<lb/>
in the Ocean.<lb/>
In which carried by currents towards<lb/>
the equator it is again accumulated<lb/>
in strata and formed by the <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">powers</unclear>
            <lb/>
of aqueous consolidation into new Rocks<lb/>
and new mountains which rise at<lb/>
length above the waves and offer<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="62"
                xml:id="pb-62"
                facs="#i62"/>
            <lb/>
a due compensation for the destruction<lb/>
of parts of ancient continents and Islands<lb/>
This Hypothesis in which the waters<lb/>
of the Atmosphere are supposed to be<lb/>
the destroying cause and the water<lb/>
of the sea the regenerating cause<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the solid land</hi> is supported by the<lb/>
Author with considerable address and<lb/>
ingenuity -<lb/>
He endeavours to prove from the<lb/>
shells and remains of fishes found in<lb/>
some parts of high mountains that<lb/>
the present continents must have been<lb/>
formed in the bed of the ocean -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="63"
                xml:id="pb-63"
                facs="#i63"/>
            <lb/>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <unclear>He endeavours to</unclear>
            </add>He endeavours to shew that some of the Islands<lb/>
under the equator have been very lately<lb/>
raised - And He brings forward many<lb/>
accurate instances which demonstrate<lb/>
that the sea has gained upon the land<lb/>
to some extent in many different<lb/>
parts of Europe.-<lb/>
I shall not at present enter upon a full<lb/>
discussion of these opinions for they will<lb/>
again occupy our attention in the<lb/>
examination of a much more comprehensive<lb/>
and <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag111"
                ref="#otherwork_097"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag111">
            more artfully constructed theory
        </bibl>
            </rs> that<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag112"
                ref="#person_125"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag112" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hutton.
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
I shall merely offer a few general<lb/>
observations upon them.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="64"
                xml:id="pb-64"
                facs="#i64"/>
            <lb/>
With regard to the idea that our present<lb/>
land was formed in the bosom of the<lb/>
sea by the mere action of water is<lb/>
is one that may be controverted and<lb/>
overturned with ease.-<lb/>
The greatest portion of our high rocks<lb/>
and elevated mountains are chrystalized<lb/>
masses containing no organic remains<lb/>
and not arranged in layers and they<lb/>
consist of matter wholly incapable of<lb/>
being consolidated by water such is<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag113"
                ref="#chemical_092"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag113">
          Granite
          
        </term>
            </rs> which forms a considerable<lb/>
part of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag114"
                ref="#place_247"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag114" type="place">
          Alps
        </name>
            </rs> which constitutes<lb/>
the great mountains of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag115"
                ref="#place_235"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag115" type="place">
          Scotland
        </name>
            </rs> and<lb/>
the hills and cliffs of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag116"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag116" type="place">
          Cornwall
        </name>
            </rs>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="65"
                xml:id="pb-65"
                facs="#i65"/>
            <lb/>
And stratified rocks even which seem<lb/>
themselves to have been deposited by<lb/>
water are often blended with rocks of<lb/>
another description so as rather to indicate<lb/>
a great inundation and rapid transit<lb/>
of the ocean over <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the land</hi> than a<lb/>
gradual and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">quite deposition</hi> of the<lb/>
solid matter of the earth in the bed of the sea.<lb/>
It is impossible to doubt that in the<lb/>
lapse of ages some slight <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">dimunition</unclear>
            <lb/>
of our mountains must take place from<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">agency of rivers</hi> but there are many<lb/>
causes in Nature which appears<lb/>
to counteract the effect.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="66"
                xml:id="pb-66"
                facs="#i66"/>
            <lb/>
Centuries nearly have passed away and<lb/>
no material change in the form of the<lb/>
solid matter of the Globe has taken<lb/>
place in consequence of this agency.<lb/>
From the most accurate observation it<lb/>
appears nearly a hundred years would<lb/>
be consumed before a single inch of<lb/>
a Rock like that which this represents<lb/>
or of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag117"
                ref="#place_1315"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag117" type="place">
          Mount Blanch
        </name>
            </rs> would be lost and<lb/>
with regard to the ultimate termination<lb/>
of such effects it is almost ridiculous<lb/>
to reason seriously -<lb/>
Man attached to the Globe has a limited<lb/>
sphere of action limited faculties and<lb/>
but a short period for the employment<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="67"
                xml:id="pb-67"
                facs="#i67"/>
            <lb/>
of them -<lb/>
He was not intended to waste his time in<lb/>
guesses concerning what is to take place<lb/>
in infinite duration but He was rather<lb/>
born to reason from the past and the<lb/>
present concerning his immediate and<lb/>
future destinies and philosophy as well<lb/>
as in common life He <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">only</del> ought only<lb/>
to be guided by certainties by distinct<lb/>
probabilities or by strong analogies -<lb/>
To conclude after censuring <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag118"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag118" type="person">
          M. Buffons
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
wilder speculations it would be unfair<lb/>
to deny to him the highest praise for<lb/>
order of arrangement splendor of description<lb/>
and brilliancy of stile -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="68"
                xml:id="pb-68"
                facs="#i68"/>
            <lb/>
He has adorned a subject of the most<lb/>
abstracted kind in the refined charms<lb/>
and elegancies of literature and He<lb/>
has bestowed on it an interest which<lb/>
it had never professed before.<lb/>
His merit in this respect is<lb/>
transcendent - there is nothing highly<lb/>
difficult in the task of delineating<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Human character</hi> in painting the<lb/>
passions and affections of the mind,<lb/>
with eloquence and with feeling -<lb/>
for these belong to all minds, all<lb/>
climes and all ages and their<lb/>
effects are <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">universal</del> universal -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="69"
                xml:id="pb-69"
                facs="#i69"/>
            <lb/>
But to cloath <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the</add> dull and dead objects<lb/>
of a speculative branch of science in<lb/>
the form of beauty and to infuse into<lb/>
them animation and life -<lb/>
This is indeed a work which the strongest<lb/>
genius only can accomplish; and it<lb/>
is a work in which <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag119"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag119" type="person">
          Buffon
        </name>
            </rs> has<lb/>
perfectly <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">succeeded</hi>.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="70"
                xml:id="pb-70"
                facs="#i70"/>
            <lb/>
